<span class="contnote">\[paragraph continues\]</span> Next to these, and
sometimes preferred to them, was Thursday, the day of Columba.

Friday is unlucky and banned because Christ was put to death on that
day. It is not permissible to begin ploughing, reaping, cutting peats,
clipping sheep, nor even to cut hair on Friday. If peat-cutting is begun
on Friday, some one will remark, 'Tha cuideigin an seo an diugh nach
faic a mhoine seo loisgte'--There is some one here to-day who will not
see these peats burnt. All feel more than they say.

No burial occurs on a Friday, nor any other work necessitating the use
of iron. Even the fairies were not allowed to appear on Friday:

